(with Paul Shafer) 

![VisualAbstract](images/visualabstract.pdf)

 In this paper, we assess the extent to which commercially-insured patients continue to pay out of pocket for preventive care. We find that the aggregate burden associated with these supposedly free services ranges between $75 million and $225 million annually.
 
[Read the full paper here!](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0091743521002590?dgcid=author)

Recommended citation: Hoagland, A., & Shafer, P. (2021). Out-of-pocket costs for preventive care persist almost a decade after the Affordable Care Act. Preventive Medicine, 150. 
